folder: Jumel Terrace & Sylvan Terrace, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Jumel Terrace, West Side and North of Sylvan Terrace. Jumel Terrace is so named from Stephen Jumel, who bought the surrounding property in 1810. Jumel Terrace is a short street running parallel to Amsterdam Avenue, from West 160th to 162nd Street.
On the East side is the old Jumel Mansion and Roger Morris Park, the latter named for Captain Roger Morris, who built the house in 1758.

P.L. Sperr,

(2)
Same.
P.L. Sperr,

(3)
Same. Close up of Mansion.
P.L. Sperr,

October 12th, 1934
April 27th, 1941

title: Manhattan: Jumel Terrace - Sylvan Terrace

folder: Sylvan Terrace & Jumel Terrace, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1) and (2)

Sylvan Terrace (formerly Sylven Place), west from Jumel Terrace. This little block of wooden houses, terminating in an elevation on the east side of St. Nicholas Avenue, was a real estate development of the early 1880's, when this part of town was still suburban. See also Jumel Terrace, and St. Nicholas Avenue, east side, from 160th to 162nd Streets. The building in the background is on the west side of St. Nicholas Avenue.
October 12, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)

The same, hardly showing the south side at all.
October 12, 1934.

P. L. Sperr.

(3)

The same different angle.

April 27, 1941.
